## RESTful API Design & Routing

### CRITICAL RULE: Clean, Scalable API Structure

**All APIs must follow RESTful principles with clear resource hierarchy and consistent patterns.**

### API Path Structure Rules

#### 1. Category-Scoped Endpoints

**ALL endpoints for a feature category MUST be prefixed with the category name.**

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD: All test-management endpoints under /test-management/
GET    /test-management/providers
POST   /test-management/projects/:projectId/integrations
GET    /test-management/integrations/:integrationId
POST   /test-management/test-runs
GET    /test-management/test-runs/:runId

// ❌ BAD: Mixed, inconsistent paths
GET    /providers                    // No category context
POST   /integrations                 // Could be ANY integration
GET    /test-status                  // Unclear what this is for
```

**Why this matters:**
- ✅ Clear separation between integration categories (test-management vs slack vs jira)
- ✅ No conflicts when adding new integration types
- ✅ Easy to understand API scope at a glance
- ✅ Frontend can organize API calls by category
- ✅ Middleware can be applied category-wide

#### 2. RESTful Resource Identification

**Resource IDs belong in URL paths, NOT query parameters or request bodies.**

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD: Resource ID in URL path
GET    /test-management/test-runs/:runId
POST   /test-management/test-runs/:runId/reset
DELETE /test-management/integrations/:integrationId

// ❌ BAD: Resource ID in query or body
GET    /test-management/test-status?runId=123        // ❌ ID in query
POST   /test-management/test-runs/reset              // ❌ ID in body
         Body: { runId: "123" }
DELETE /test-management/integrations?id=456          // ❌ ID in query
```

**Standard REST Verbs:**
- `GET` - Read/Retrieve
- `POST` - Create or Action
- `PUT` - Full Update
- `PATCH` - Partial Update (use sparingly)
- `DELETE` - Remove

#### 3. Collection vs Single Resource Pattern

**Use `projectId` (or parent resource ID) ONLY for collection-level operations (CREATE, LIST).**

For single-resource operations (GET, PUT, DELETE), the resource's own ID is sufficient.

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD: Collection operations use parent ID
POST   /test-management/projects/:projectId/integrations    // Create in project
GET    /test-management/projects/:projectId/integrations    // List project's integrations
POST   /test-management/projects/:projectId/configs         // Create in project
GET    /test-management/projects/:projectId/configs         // List project's configs

// ✅ GOOD: Single-resource operations use resource ID only
GET    /test-management/integrations/:integrationId         // ID is enough
PUT    /test-management/integrations/:integrationId         // ID is enough
DELETE /test-management/integrations/:integrationId         // ID is enough
GET    /test-management/configs/:configId                   // ID is enough
PUT    /test-management/configs/:configId                   // ID is enough

// ❌ BAD: Redundant projectId in single-resource operations
GET    /test-management/projects/:projectId/integrations/:integrationId  // ❌ Redundant
PUT    /test-management/projects/:projectId/configs/:configId            // ❌ Redundant
```

**Why:**
- Each resource ID (integrationId, configId) is globally unique
- Backend can look up the project from the resource ID if needed
- Cleaner, shorter URLs
- Standard REST pattern

#### 4. Provider-Specific Endpoints

**Provider-specific operations MUST include the provider type in the URL.**

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD: Provider type explicit in URL
GET    /test-management/integrations/:integrationId/checkmate/metadata/projects
GET    /test-management/integrations/:integrationId/checkmate/metadata/squads
GET    /test-management/integrations/:integrationId/testrail/metadata/suites

// ❌ BAD: Generic metadata endpoints
GET    /test-management/integrations/:integrationId/metadata/projects    // ❌ Which provider?
GET    /test-management/integrations/:integrationId/metadata/squads      // ❌ Not all providers have squads
```

**Why:**
- Different providers have different metadata structures
- Prevents runtime errors from calling unsupported endpoints
- Self-documenting (URL tells you what data to expect)
- Frontend can build provider-specific UI

#### 5. Action Endpoints

**For operations that aren't standard CRUD, use descriptive action names.**

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD: Clear action names
POST   /test-management/integrations/:integrationId/verify
POST   /test-management/test-runs/:runId/reset
POST   /test-management/test-runs/:runId/cancel

// ❌ BAD: Unclear or non-standard
POST   /test-management/integrations/:integrationId/check     // ❌ Vague
POST   /test-management/test-runs/reset?runId=123            // ❌ ID not in URL
GET    /test-management/test-runs/:runId/cancel              // ❌ Wrong verb (should be POST)
```

**Action Naming:**
- Use verbs: `verify`, `reset`, `cancel`, `activate`, `retry`
- Always use `POST` for actions (they cause side effects)
- Keep action names short and clear

#### 6. Query Parameters

**Use query parameters for filtering, pagination, sorting - NOT for resource identification.**

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD: Query params for filtering/options
GET    /test-management/projects/:projectId/configs?providerType=CHECKMATE
GET    /test-management/test-runs/:runId/report?groupBy=section
GET    /test-management/integrations/:integrationId/checkmate/metadata/sections?projectId=100

// ❌ BAD: Query params for resource ID
GET    /test-management/configs?id=123                      // ❌ Should be path param
GET    /test-management/test-runs?runId=456                 // ❌ Should be path param
```

**Valid query param uses:**
- Filtering: `?providerType=CHECKMATE`, `?status=active`
- Pagination: `?page=2&limit=50`
- Sorting: `?sortBy=createdAt&order=desc`
- Options: `?groupBy=section`, `?includeArchived=true`
- Secondary resources: `?projectId=100` (when the primary resource is integrationId)

### Complete Example: Test Management APIs

**Correct, production-ready API structure:**

```typescript
// 1. PROVIDERS (Discovery)
GET    /test-management/providers

// 2. PROJECT INTEGRATIONS (Credentials)
POST   /test-management/projects/:projectId/integrations      // Create
GET    /test-management/projects/:projectId/integrations      // List
GET    /test-management/integrations/:integrationId           // Get
PUT    /test-management/integrations/:integrationId           // Update
DELETE /test-management/integrations/:integrationId           // Delete
POST   /test-management/integrations/:integrationId/verify    // Action

// 3. CONFIGS (Test configurations)
